



Dear Sir
Amsterdam March 1. 1781



The Letters I received at Leyden, obliged me to leave you Sooner than I intended,1 but <I did not know>, I shall soon See you again, at the Hague.
I have received, important Dispatches from Congress, upon which I want your Advice. I hope it is no bad News. You will Say nothing, reflect well upon the Times, and be prepared to answer me, serious Questions upon public Affairsnothing personalnor selfishnor little. I shall See you, in the Course of next Weekif nothing turns up, to prevent it, which I dont foresee. Dont raise your Expectations too highrememberNil Admirari.2

Adieu

